==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in early 15th century.
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|accompanien|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|acompagner||to associate with|lang=fro}}, from {{term|compaign||companion|lang=fro}}. See [[company]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkʌm.pə.ni/|/ə.ˈkʌmp.ni/}}
* {{audio|en-us-accompany.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|accompan|i|ed}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To go with or attend as a companion or associate; to keep company with; to go along with.
#* '''1804''' [[w:Richard Glover (poet)|Richard Glover]]:
#*: The Persian dames, […] / In sumptuous cars, '''accompanied''' his march.
#* '''1581''', {{w|Philip Sidney}}, ''An Apology of Poetry, or a Defense of Poesy'', Book I:
#*: They are never alone that are '''accompanied''' with noble thoughts.
#* '''1979''', {{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay}}, ''The History of England'':
#*: He was '''accompanied''' by two carts filled with wounded rebels.
#: {{usex|Geoffrey '''accompanied''' the group on their pilgrimage.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To supplement with; add to.
#*{{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=5
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=He was thinking; but the glory of the song, the swell from the great organ, the clustered lights, […], the height and vastness of this noble fane, its antiquity and its strength—all these things seemed to have their part as causes of the thrilling emotion that '''accompanied''' his thoughts.}}
#{{senseid|en|to perform an accompanying part next to another instrument}}{{context|intransitive|music|lang=en}} To perform an accompanying part or parts in a [[composition]].
# {{context|transitive|music|lang=en}} To perform an accompanying part next to another instrument.
#: {{usex|The strings were '''accompanied''' by two woodwinds.}}
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To associate in a company; to keep company.
#* {{rfdate}} Holland:
#*: Men say that they will drive away one another, […] and not '''accompany''' together.
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[cohabit]] (with).
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To cohabit with; to coexist with; occur with.
{{rfex|the obsolete cases}}

====Usage notes====
{{sense|to go with}} Persons are said to be accompanied '''by''', and inanimate objects, state or condition is said to be accompanied '''with'''.

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|go with}} [[attend]], [[escort]], go with
:* We '''accompany''' those with whom we go as companions. The word imports an ''equality'' of station.
:* We '''attend''' those whom we wait upon or follow. The word conveys an idea of ''subordination''.
:* We '''escort''' those whom we attend with a view to ''guard and protect''.
:*: A gentleman '''accompanies''' a friend to some public place; he '''attends''' or '''escorts''' a lady.

